&gt; The theme of JUnit 4 is to encourage more developers to write more tests by
&gt; further simplifying JUnit. To this end, we have followed NUnit&#39;s lead in
&gt; identifying tests by annotation instead of subclassing and naming
&gt; conventions. Tests can now live in any class. Tell JUnit they are there with
&gt; the @Test annotation:
&gt;   @Test public void basicTransaction() {...
&gt; 
&gt; The assertion methods are in an Assert class which is most easily used
&gt; through static import:
&gt;   import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;
&gt;   ...
&gt;   @Test public void example() {...assertEquals(2, 2);...}
&gt; 
&gt; Set up and tear down are handled with the @Before and @After annotations.
&gt; You can have as many @Befores and @Afters as you need. Inherited @Befores
&gt; are executed before @Befores in subclasses and inherited @Afters are
&gt; executed after @Afters in subclasses.
&gt; 
&gt; Shared setup is handled by @BeforeClass and @AfterClass. Methods with these
&gt; annotations are executed once before (respectively after) all the tests in
&gt; the class run.
&gt; 
&gt; @Ignore causes a test not to be run, but it is reported as ignored.
&gt; 
&gt; @Test takes two optional parameters. A test annotated @Test(timeout=100)
&gt; will fail if the test takes longer than 100 milliseconds to complete. A test
&gt; annotated @Test(expected=NullPointerException.class) will fail if a
&gt; NullPointerException is not thrown and succeed if a NullPointerException is
&gt; thrown.
&gt; 
&gt; Preserving existing investment in tests has taken nearly half of our
&gt; development effort. JUnit 4 is forward and backward compatible. You can run
&gt; older tests with the JUnit 4 test runner by passing them to the runner. You
&gt; can run JUnit 4 tests with older test runners by wrapping the JUnit 4 test
&gt; class in a compatibility class. The following method in a JUnit 4 test class
&gt; causes it to run correctly with the Eclipse test runner.
&gt;   public static junit.framework.Test suite() {
&gt;     return new JUnit4TestAdapter(AssertionTest.class);
&gt;   }
&gt; 
&gt; JUnit 4&#39;s command line interface can be invoked with:
&gt;   java org.junit.runner.JUnitCore Test1 Test2
&gt; 
&gt; The same interface can be invoked programmatically with:
&gt;   JUnitCore.run(Test1.class, Test2.class);
&gt; 
&gt; If you want to know more about the details of JUnit 4, you can browse the
&gt; tests in org.junit.tests.*.
&gt; 
&gt; Erich and I will be participating on the JUnit lists to discuss further
&gt; simplification of JUnit 4, integration with test runners, and experiences
&gt; using it. Our experience with it (most of the tests were written JUnit 4
&gt; style) has been very positive. The complexity of JUnit 3.x is like a tiny
&gt; pebble in a shoe. It doesn&#39;t seem like much until it is gone.
&gt; 
&gt; Good testing,
&gt; 
&gt; Kent Beck
&gt; Three Rivers Institute
